AB  - Design is a way of thinking where adaptability and simplicity carry value for the end-user. Any interactions with technologies and systems need to be cognitively adapted to be intuitive, culturally aligned and trustworthy. The emotional output of successful interaction with valuable design is a series of moments of serendipity for the user. Successful design feels right. In order to create such moments, the designer needs to not only emphasize with the users, but also know the culture surrounding the user, and the cognitive apparatus applied by the user. Design thinking characterized by prospective empathy with users will take the form of a dynamic discipline of prototyping, and can only take place in a culture with a tolerance for failure. The best means for creating efficient user-centered design and future user interactions will be by developing a dynamic and flexible organizational culture with as little internal competition as possible. Designers feeling or experiencing emotional threats will no longer have the right emotional resources to fully empathize with the end-user and any design will deteriorate as a result, along with trust (see Chapter 19 for an introduction to organizational culture fostering design thinking). Furthermore, in digitized and advanced big-data analytics, trust is inevitably rooted in the functionality of the design. Unless privacy and data handling is aligned to the individual user, in a targeted culture, product demand will suffer as a function of violation of privacy. © Marika Lüders, Tor W. Andreassen, Simon Clatworthy and Tore Hillestad 2017. All rights reserved.
